<DOC>
<DOCID> nyt960830.0602 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=a pri=u> A0326 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=tdt-z> BC-HELICOPTER-REPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">08-30</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0680 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-HELICOPTER-REPORT-BOS
OVERSIGHT FAULTED IN POLICE HELICOPTER CRASH REPORT
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">New York Times News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">THOMAS C. PALMER JR.</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">The Boston Globe</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">BOSTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  &UR;  &LR; Top <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> officials were warned of management
problems within the air wing even before the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">February 1995</TIMEX>
helicopter crash that killed two troopers and two civilians,
according to a report issued <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   The final administrative report of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> on the crash
repeats the <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October 1995</TIMEX> findings of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation
Safety Board</ENAMEX> on the two contributing causes of the crash  &MD;  <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State
Police</ENAMEX> management's failure to provide adequate oversight of the
air wing, and fuel contamination from an poorly maintained facility
in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Framingham</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   But the report adds explicitly that a third cause of the
aircraft's crash into a <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Memorial Drive</ENAMEX> boathouse in <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Cambridge</ENAMEX> was
``failure of the pilot to execute a proper autorotation,'' a safety
procedure designed to allow an emergency landing after engine
failure.
<p>
   The crash of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Eurocopter</ENAMEX> ASTAR craft killed two
state police troopers and pilots, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">James Mattaliano</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Paul Perry</ENAMEX>,
and two civilian employees of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">AT&AMP;T</ENAMEX> who were also aboard, <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Arthur
Howell</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Michael McCarthy</ENAMEX>.
<p>
   <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>'s report chronicled two instances in which warnings were
sent to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> management pointing to problems in its
aviation wing.
<p>
   In one case, a civilian manager at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Norwood Airport</ENAMEX> reported
observing ``a lack of training activity'' among the police unit and
reported complaints about ``training practices and
professionalism'' within the air wing.
<p>
   That manager, who is unnamed but is employed by a company that
is a defendant in a lawsuit resulting from the accident, met with
top <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> officials in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1993</TIMEX> to express his concerns.
<p>
   Although he recalls telling the officials, including Secretary
of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Public Safety</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Kathleen O'Toole</ENAMEX> that ``pilots no longer seemed to
practice autorotations when returning from a mission as had been
past practice,'' neither <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">O'Toole</ENAMEX> nor two state police majors who
attended the meeting recalled that specific warning.
<p>
   In addition to that manager's warning, in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">March 1994</TIMEX> Sgt.
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Richard Welby</ENAMEX>, an air-wing pilot, wrote a report containing his
belief that officers were not being adequately trained in emergency
procedures. All pilots later received training, though a
recommendation for advanced training had been denied because of a
lack of funding.
<p>
   The report issued <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Welby</ENAMEX>'s concerns were communicated
to Col. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Charles Henderson</ENAMEX>, but <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Henderson</ENAMEX> ``does not recall
receiving the document.'' <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Henderson</ENAMEX> has since retired as head of
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> after being pressured to leave, in part because of
the fatal crash.
<p>
   One <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> lieutenant said that, although the wing met
technical training requirements, ``he did not feel that formal
training was up to the standards one would expect.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">O'Toole</ENAMEX> issued a statement <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Friday</TIMEX>, saying, ``My thoughts and
prayers go out to the families of the crash victims as they once
again relive the tragedy that befell us all. Although nothing can
be done to return those lost I am pleased with the comprehensive
nature of this report.''
<p>
   The report reviews significant changes that have been made since
the crash, and others that are planned.
<p>
   So far, aviation consultants have been hired to reorganize the
air wing, the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Department of State Police</ENAMEX> is seeking additional
money to replace aircraft and ground facilities, more training has
been required of air-wing managers, and the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Framingham</ENAMEX> fuel
facility has been permanently closed.
<p>
   The report ruled out any acts of sabotage, but it said that
among police management there was ``organizational confusion
resulting from a lack of designated responsibility'' for taking
care of the fuel facility.
<p>
   Water contamination in the fuel found in the system of the
wrecked helicopter ranged from 2.5 to nine times the allowable
limit.
<p>
   ``We have learned from this tragedy,'' says the report, signed
by <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Reed V. Hillman</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">State Police</ENAMEX> superintendent.
</TEXT>
